</P>
<P>
1 SCRANTON PAPER BUYS THE OTHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SCRANTON, Pa. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scranton's oldest newspaper, the Scrantonian Tribune, was purchased by its 
longtime rival, the Scranton Times, and ceased publication today. 
</P>
<P>
Employees arriving for work at the newspaper were told that today's edition 
would be the last. 
</P>
<P>
In the Tribune newsroom, someone scrawled "30" -- the symbol traditionally used 
by reporters at the end of a story -- on a locker. 
</P>
<P>
MediaOne Inc., which bought the Scrantonian Publishing Co. from the Goodman 
family of Scranton in 1987, announced the newspaper's demise in a brief 
release. 
</P>
<P>
"The deteriorating economic conditions affecting the Northeast no longer made 
it economically viable to publish a second newspaper in the Scranton market," 
MediaOne said. 
</P>
<P>
The Scranton Times, which published an afternoon newspaper for many years, 
launched a morning edition, the Morning Times, in 1988 to compete directly with 
the Tribune. 
</P>
</TEXT>
